\section{Derivation of the objective function}

A firm $i$ is characterized by its number of employees $e_i$ and the average productivity per employee, $\pi_i$. 
Assume for simplicity that the production function of the firm is linear w.r.t. labor, i.e. proportional to the number of employees, so that the dollar value of what the firm produces is $\pi_i e_i$.  Let's also assume that the costs are proportional to the number of workers with proportionality constant $w_i$, i.e. 
the firm's labor cost is $c_i=w_ie_i$, where $w_i$ is the wage (which for convenience we will assume is the same for all employees).  There may be others costs as well, but to keep the notation simple let's assume for now that they scale linearly with the number of workers and are included in $w_i$, and that there are no other costs.

Assume that at any given time the demand for the firms good is $D_i$.  In the ideal case the firm has exactly the right amount of workers to satisfy the demand, $D_i = e_i \pi_i$, but in general there may be a mismatch.  If there are too many workers then the firm pays for more labor than it needs, and if there are not enough workers then the firm pays an opportunity cost because it is not able to produce enough to satisfy the full demand.  The firm's revenue $r_i=min(D_i,p_i)$ and its profit $\Pi_i$ is
\begin{eqnarray}
    &\Pi_i=r_i-c_i = min(D_i,\pi_i e_i) - w_i e_i.
\end{eqnarray}
Since all terms are indexed by $i$, we will drop it for the moment.

The optimal number of workers is $D/\pi$.  The firm's lost profit $\Delta \Pi \le 0$ is the difference between the profit it makes with its actual number of workers and the profit it would have made with the optimal number of workers.  When it has the optimal number of workers, $\pi e = D$ and $\Delta \Pi = 0$.  When it has too many workers, $\pi e > D$, and
$$\Delta \Pi = D - w e  -(D - w D/\pi) = w (D/\pi - e),$$
and when it has too few workers,  $\pi e < D$, 
$$\Delta \Pi = \pi e - w e  - (D - w D/\pi) = e (\pi - w)  - D (1 - w/\pi).$$
Note that if $w = \pi$, the firm makes no profits, even with the optimal number of workers.  In this case, when there are too many workers, $\Delta \Pi =  D - \pi e < 0$, but when there are too few workers, $\Delta \Pi = 0$, independent of the worker imbalance.   This means that the firm loses money when it has more workers than it needs, but when it has too few workers, the loss in revenue is equal to the reduction in costs, so $\Delta \Pi = 0$.  Here we will instead assume that $\pi > w$, which means that the firm charges a markup $\mu = \pi / w - 1 > 0$ so that it always makes a profit in the ideal case where $\pi e = D.$
For some purposes it is more useful to think in relative terms by defining the workforce efficiency $\mathcal{E} = \Pi^{actual}/\Pi^{ideal} $.  The efficiency is at most one, but it can also become negative.  When there are too many workers, i.e. when  $\pi e > D$, the efficiency is
$$\mathcal{E} = \frac{D - w e}{D - w D/\pi} =  \frac{1 - w e/D}{1 - w/\pi}. $$
To make this more intuitive, let $\tilde{e} = D/\pi$ be the optimal number of employees at any given time.  Then we can write
$$\mathcal{E} =  \frac{1 - w e/\pi \tilde{e}}{1 - w/\pi} = \frac{1 + \mu - e/\tilde{e}}{\mu}. $$
The efficiency is positive as long as $1 + \mu - e/\tilde{e} > 0.$  This also corresponds to the condition for profitability, i.e. $\Pi = \pi \tilde{e} - w e > 0$.  When the markup is low, e.g. 10\%, this means that the firm can become unprofitable with a relatively small excess number of workers, e.g. 10\% more than the optimal number of workers.   
When there are too few workers, i.e. when $\pi e < D$, the efficiency is $$\mathcal{E} = \frac{\pi e - w e}{D - w D/\pi} =  \frac{e}{\tilde{e}}. $$

This is always positive unless demand goes to zero and the firm fires all its workers.  This illustrates that the penalties for having more vs. less workers is asymmetric -- the penalty for having too many workers is potentially much worse than the penalty for having too few workers.  This is illustrated in the figure.

