\section{Employment and vacancy dynamics}

Assume that the demand $D_{it}$ for the product of firm $i$ changes in time.  The firm wishes to maximize its expected profits $E[\Pi_{it}]$.   While it might like to always adjust its employees so that $e_{it} = \tilde{e}_{it}$, in general this will not be possible due to the fact that hiring new employees takes time.  The dynamics of the employment $e_{it}$ for firm $i$ are given by
\\\begin{equation}
    \Delta e_{it} = h_tv_{it}\Delta t  - s e_{it}\Delta t - F_{it}\Delta t,
\end{equation}
where $\Delta e_{it} = e_{i,t+\Delta t} - e_{it}$ is the change in the number of employees in the interval of length $\Delta t$ between $t$ and $t+ \Delta t$, $v_{it} \ge 0$ is the number of vacancies posted at time $t$, $h_t \ge 0$ is the rate at which employees are hired, $s \ge 0$ is the spontaneous separation rate, and $F_{it} \ge 0$ is the firing rate.  In general hiring is a stochastic process, but here for simplicity assume that it is deterministic so that $h_t v_{it}$ employees are hired in each interval $\Delta t$, and for now let the number of employees be a positive real number.  The rate at which workers ``spontaneously" exit the firm is $s e_{it}$, where we will assume for now that the separation rate $s$ is a constant that is independent of the firm and independent of time.  This represents both workers who quit or retire as well as workers that might be fired for reasons that are not related to changes in demand.  The firing rate $F_{it}$ represents firing above and beyond the spontaneous rate, driven by changes in demand.

We can use this as an iterated map by choosing time units where $\Delta t = 1$ or alternatively divide through by $\Delta t$, take the limit as it goes to zero, and write this as a differential equation,
\begin{equation}
    \frac{de_{i}}{dt} = h(u) v_{i}(t)  - s e_{i}(t) - F_{i}(t),
\end{equation}
where here we write $h(u)$ to emphasize that the hiring rate will depend on the level of unemployment, defined later, which is an aggregate quantity that depends not just on firm $i$ but on all the firms in the economy.

We assume that the functions $v$ and $F$ that specify hiring and firing are the same for all firms.  The firms vacancies are given by $v_i(t)= v(x_{it}, f^{\tau}_t)$, where $x_{it} = (e_{it} - \tilde{e}_{it})$ is the worker imbalance for firm $i$ at time $t$ and $f^{\tau}_t$ is the firm's probabilistic forecast made at time $t$ for demand at time $t + \tau$, which depends on the underlying stochastic process $D_{it}$.    Assume that when a firm fires workers this instantly reduces the number of workers.   In contrast, as already noted, hiring workers takes time.  For now we will assume that all firms have the same hiring rate, though in reality firms in different sectors or geographic locations, or firms offering different wages, may have very different hiring rates $h_{it}$.



