We will begin by writing down a possible hiring and firing strategy that a firm might follow and explore the vacancy and unemployment dynamics that it generates.  This should be regarded as a heuristic -- it is not clear that there is any demand process for which it is optimal -- but it is a guess at a strategy that may be a reasonable approximation of an optimal strategy for some stochastic processes for the demand.

Consider the following hiring and firing strategy: 
\begin{eqnarray}
v_{it} & = & \left[  s e_{it} /h_t - x_{it}\right]^+_{0}, \\
\nonumber
F_{it} & = &  [x_{it} - s e_{it} /h_t + h_t v_{it}]^+_{\theta },\\
\nonumber
\theta &=& \alpha e_{it}/\tilde{e}_{it}.
\end{eqnarray}
The bracket function $ [x]^+_y $ is equal to its argument when it is greater than $y$ and zero otherwise.  See the plot in figure 2, which gives an example with $\theta = 0$ and another example with $\theta = 100$ workers.
