To understand the equation for vacancies, first assume demand is constant and that at time $t$ the firm has the desired number of workers, i.e. $x_{it} = 0$.  The firm anticipates that during the interval $\Delta t$ between $t$ and $t+1$,  $s e_{it} $ workers will be spontaneously separated.  If the firm were to post $s e_{it}$ vacancies, i.e. if it were to post vacancies only for the jobs of the workers that separate in that period,  it will on average hire $h_t e_{it}s $ replacements in the next period of length $\Delta t$, so in the typical case where $h_t < 1$ it will not have as many workers as it needs.  This means that in order to have $x_{i, t+1} = 0$, it must post  $ e_{it}s/h_t $ vacancies.   If $x_{it} > 0$ this means that the firm has more workers than it needs.  In this case it will post fewer vacancies, and if $e_{it} s/h_t - x_{it} \le 0$, it will post no vacancies at all.

To understand the equation for the firing rate, again first let $\theta = 0$.  In this case the firing strategy $F$ is chosen to anticipate how many workers there will be at time $t+1$ absent firing, and fire as many as needed so that $x_{i, t+1} = 0$.  The anticipated number of  extra workers absent firing is $\hat{x}_{i,t+1} = x_t - s e_{it}/h_t + h_t v_{it}$.  If $x_{it} = 0$, then the vacancy rate has already been chosen to that $h_t v_{it} = s e_{it}/h_t$, so the second two terms sum to zero.  However, if $x_{it} > 0$ then the vacancies have already been reduced in order to reduce the number of workers at time $t+1$.  The inclusion of this term inside the brackets ensures that firing only takes place if it is not possible to reduce the number of workers at time $t+1$ by reducing the vacancies.

The strategy above incorporates the principle that a firm will stop hiring before it starts firing.  This can be viewed as a behavioral rule but it may also make sense rationally.  It is less traumatic for a firm to stop or reduce hiring than it is for it to fire people.  Firing can reduce workforce morale.  A firm might avoid firing to make its workers feel better, but this may also be the best strategy to maximize long-term profits.  Thus this can be viewed as a behavioral modification of profit maximization or it could in fact be a profit maximizing strategy. 

Letting $\theta > 0$ introduces a buffer, allowing an excess of workers up to a limit $\theta$, as shown in Figure 2(b).  Note that when the threshold is hit, the firm fires 100 workers at once, which reduces its workforce from 150 to 50.  Since vacancies are zero, with the expected worker separations, this ensures the $x_{i,t+1} = 0$, i.e. it brings the workforce to the ideal number on the next timestep. A strategy with a buffer makes sense, for example, if the firm has too many workers, but it anticipates that demand will soon rise again and doesn't want to fire workers that would take time to replace in the future.   To make the algorithm independent of size, we choose $\theta = \alpha e_{it}/\tilde{e}_{it}$, where $\alpha \ge 0$; this makes it possible to adjust the size of the buffer proportional to the size of the firm, so that the same value of $\alpha$ can be used for firms of all sizes.  The use of $\theta > 0$ also makes behavioral sense.  It means that firing workers is less common, but when it occurs, there is a large layoff that gets the firing over with.  By analogy with sticky wages, this can be thought of as ``sticky employment".  

Note that for vacancies $\theta = 0$.  The rationale is that if the firm has too many workers, it will not want to post vacancies in any case. 

The performance of this strategy, or any other strategy, will depend on the random process for the demand $D_{it}$.  Suppose, for example, that $D$ follows a random walk, so that it is equally likely to go up or down.  If the loss function were symmetric, the strategy with $\theta = 0$ might be optimal.  However, the loss is larger if there are excess workers than if there are too few workers, which may complicated this -- it might even imply that the firm is better off ensuring a buffer so that it typically doesn't fully satisfy demand.  Making $\theta > 0$ results in more tolerance for excess workers, which could make this worse.  Though if demand is growing, e.g. if it is a random walk with positive drift, it might make sense to let $\theta > 0$.  (We should consider using the actual GDP process rather than the detrended GDP process, as this is what real firms face.)

 A more realistic model is that demand is correlated to GDP, in which case it should follow a similar process.  The fact that GDP follows an AR processes indicates that it mean reverts, which implies that if GDP is below its trend, it is more likely to increase.  This in turn means that a strategy with $\theta > 0$ might do better than a strategy with $\theta = 0$.  (If we do use actual GDP rather than detrended GDP we will need to adjust the AR process so that it reverts to an ever-increasing value rather than reverting to a constant value). 

 An economist would begin by assuming that the firms forecasts are consistent with the underlying random process that GDP follows, and try to derive the hiring and firing strategy that maximizes their profits when this is true.  This is non-trivial, because the firm needs to plan more than one step into the future to do this optimally.  A typical approach would involve writing down a Bellman equation and trying to solve it.  This is hard -- I don't think we should do that now, but it is worth thinking about what that might entail, and we might want to consider making a myopic approximation, such as finding a strategy that optimizes one step ahead.